name: 3-fluoro-4-methylphenylacetic acid
Reason: To predict the melting point of 3-fluoro-4-methylphenylacetic acid, we start from the basic unit, benzene, which has a typical melting point around 5.5°C. The following functional groups will affect the melting point: - The methyl group (+CH3) typically increases the melting point due to a slight increase in molecular weight and bulk, but because it also tends to disrupt the crystal packing this effect might be modest, let's estimate it as a +5°C increase. - The fluoro group (F) generally increases the melting point due to its electronegativity, which leads to stronger intermolecular interactions such as dipole-dipole forces. A halogen like fluorine could increase the melting point significantly, so we might estimate an increase of +20°C. - The phenyl group itself (when substituted on a carbon chain like in phenylacetic acid) will have a different effect than it does in benzene. It tends to raise the melting point due to increased pi-pi stacking possibilities and increased molecular rigidity. The increase might be around +50°C. - The acetic acid group (-COOH) will dramatically increase the melting point due to the ability for hydrogen bonding. Since it allows for the formation of hydrogen-bonded dimers, this can largely increase the melting point, perhaps by an additional +80°C. Combining these effects gives us an estimated increase of 5 (methyl) + 20 (fluoro) + 50 (phenyl) + 80 (acetic acid) based on benzene as the starting point.
